<p>History makes the pattern clear. In the 1970s, gold rose from roughly <strong>$35/oz to over $800/oz</strong> as Bretton Woods collapsed, inflation surged, and faith in paper currencies weakened. In 2008, gold initially fell in the liquidation phase—because investors sold what they could, not just what they disliked—but then climbed from roughly <strong>$700–800/oz in late 2008 to about $1,900/oz by 2011</strong> as rates collapsed and quantitative easing spread. In 2020, the same sequence repeated: a brief dash-for-cash decline, then a surge above <strong>$2,000/oz</strong> once real yields fell and policy stimulus exploded.</p>
